\fs36 What is CabConverter 2?
\fs28 \

\fs24 CabConverter 2 (or just "CabConverter" for the remainder of this document) is a program that converts electronic ham radio logs used in radio contests into a format suitable for submission to contest sponsors. CabConverter is not a logging program; CabConverter is a report generator that takes data from an .ADIF file exported from a logging program and produces a new report file in a format called 
\i Cabrillo
\i0 .\
\
If you wish to participate in any of the large radio contests such as CQ World Wide or the ARRL DX you must be able to produce a log file in a format acceptable to those contest sponsors. While most contests still accept a radio log written on paper, contest submissions in the form of computer log files in Cabrillo format are preferred. There will likely come a day when only computer log files will be accepted.\
\

\fs36 A bit of history
\fs28 \

\fs24 The original Cab-Converter program (note the "-" in the name) was written by me, B. Scott Andersen (just "Scott", please) in 2002. I had just been licensed and had tried my hand at contesting in the CQ WW SSB contest. I had selected MacLoggerDX from Dog Park Software ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.dogparksoftware.com/"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 http://www.dogparksoftware.com/}}) as my logging program and had gotten rig control working. A Heil headset, foot pedal, and nice computer logging software seemed all I needed to get started.\
\
When the contest was over I realized that I had missed a step: I needed a way to convert my log into 
\i Cabrillo
\i0  format so it could be submitted to CQ Magazine's in-box. What should I do? After looking around for a program to do this conversion and finding nothing that fit the bill, I decided to tackle the task myself. I wrote a very small program in Java to do the conversion. This program took as input the .ADIF export from MacLoggerDX and turned each QSO into a line in a text file in the format expected by CQ Magazine. I edited the other element needed myself within a text editor (much like the one you are using now to read this) and submitted the log. \
\
In August of 2003 I saw the results of my efforts in that month's CQ Magazine:\
\
